<div id="review_2288104290" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2288104290" />
    <a title="Yogy TheBear" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46429408-yogy-thebear"><img alt="Yogy TheBear" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1484400696p2/46429408.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2288104290?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Yogy TheBear" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Yogy TheBear" href="/user/show/46429408-yogy-thebear">Yogy TheBear</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2288104290" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17591787442218961027">Well except for his idealism, naivety, bias twords private property, idyllic conception of socialism, disregard of economics and poor understanding of human emotions and behavior… this guy would have been enjoyable and convincing. I give him 2 stars because I read much much worse from the socialist spectrum of politics.<br/>He seems to acknowledge much of the tenets of individualism but rejects private property. For him property creates power and oppression just as the state dose… yet there are much </span>
  <span id="freeText17591787442218961027" style="display:none">Well except for his idealism, naivety, bias twords private property, idyllic conception of socialism, disregard of economics and poor understanding of human emotions and behavior… this guy would have been enjoyable and convincing. I give him 2 stars because I read much much worse from the socialist spectrum of politics.<br />He seems to acknowledge much of the tenets of individualism but rejects private property. For him property creates power and oppression just as the state dose… yet there are much more things that generate this tendency… among them being your average human... How do you reform one person... Who can reform other persons... What means are suitable ? <br />He dose not conceive of the possibility of private property, competition and solidarity, all together; for him solidarity, true solidarity, comes without private property. The difficulties and dilemmas of the individuals of a community in witch the capital is common to organize production and innovation as efficient as in capitalism is not crossing his mind, I am not talking only of the calculation problem but also of problems like this: John thinks he has a better idea on how production to be organized, for it he must divert limited resources from the common stock and production to test his new idea… Can he freely divert and re-organize capital resources held in common ? What if he dose not have permission from the majority… ? Is Jhon then oppressed… ? Can society ever be in accord what must be produced ? Let us say this hurdles are resolved without the return to the apparatus and methods of the state... Well then you just have syndicalism and a free market in witch only groups that hold parts of the common stock of capital with a barter economy<br />Private property in necessary, competition as long as the means employed are in moral limits and seek to better satisfy the clients is good, solidarity can exist in this system. A system with public/common property to work requires uniformity and continuity of wants, requires that people accept that some must do hard work others not so hard work for the satisfaction of the same equal desires. This group of individuals is possible on a small scale, as in monastery, but not all of humanity. Thus anarchy with private property is way more feasible because it takes the human being as it is, not as how it should be to be absolutely good.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17591787442218961027" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


