<span id="freeTextContainer13912809654680982716">Well, its a lot better than Berkman&apos;s the ABC of Anarchy.<br/><br/>Malatesta writes lovely prose in a direct way that is not insulting to the intelligence of the reader. Mostly. So far the anarchist writings i&apos;ve read do a lot of talking and framing why Government is bad. Malatesta does a relatively decent job of this. He writes like an educated man who has read some social theory, some economic theory, some behavioral/protopsychology theory, darwinist theory. Because of hsi read background his idealism s</span>
  <span id="freeText13912809654680982716" style="display:none">Well, its a lot better than Berkman's the ABC of Anarchy.<br /><br />Malatesta writes lovely prose in a direct way that is not insulting to the intelligence of the reader. Mostly. So far the anarchist writings i've read do a lot of talking and framing why Government is bad. Malatesta does a relatively decent job of this. He writes like an educated man who has read some social theory, some economic theory, some behavioral/protopsychology theory, darwinist theory. Because of hsi read background his idealism seems more earnest and well-founded. <br /><br />But the "why government is bad" is always the easiest bit<br /><br />Ive yet to see any Anarchist literature that could explain how things work.<br /><br />Again its that "people are good and will find a way to make things work". Social cohesion is a factor of resources and economics. Always is Malatesta himself acknowledges this in some parts of the book as a way to dimiss some negative argument, but doesnt apply this to utopian view of man.<br /><br />He gives example and example of man's increasing interconnectedness, but doesnt explain how that would have been achievable in the absence of governments?<br /><br />Since Malatesta isnt an An-Com, he doesnt try to explain away economics in embarassing manners. He just washes himself of ny responsibility on how *anything would actually work*, via a large number of rhetorical questions that are outright dismissed as out of scope and impossible to answer. <br /><br />Yea ok. <br /><br />Again in the end you are left with shallow rhetoric. Still waiting on the "good anarchist literature".</span>
