  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3319056393" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3319056393" />
    <a title="Joel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20665752-joel"><img alt="Joel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1595656489p2/20665752.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3319056393?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joel" href="/user/show/20665752-joel">Joel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3319056393" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2871634971645459870">Usually, I find political theory to be dry, dense, and wholly unapproachable, but Malatesta does an excellent job of making it palatable. I&apos;m still forming my own opinions on political systems but I must say if anarchism were to exist as Malatesta describes it, things wouldn&apos;t be half bad: <blockquote>
  <i>From the free participation of all, by means of the spontaneous grouping of men according to their requirements and their sympathies...starting with the most urgent interests and arriving in the end at the </i></blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText2871634971645459870" style="display:none">Usually, I find political theory to be dry, dense, and wholly unapproachable, but Malatesta does an excellent job of making it palatable. I'm still forming my own opinions on political systems but I must say if anarchism were to exist as Malatesta describes it, things wouldn't be half bad: <blockquote>
  <i>From the free participation of all, by means of the spontaneous grouping of men according to their requirements and their sympathies...starting with the most urgent interests and arriving in the end at the most remote and most general, a social organisation would emerge the function of which would be the greatest wellbeing and the greatest freedom for everybody, and would draw together the whole of mankind into a community of comradeship...</i>
</blockquote> My understanding of anarchy after reading this is that in the absence of government people are truly free to associate with whomever they please. In our current system, we are limited by economic means or state intervention from practicing free association. <br /><br />In order to understand anarchism as the absence of a state presence, it's useful to also understand Malatesta's definition of the state and its enforcers: <blockquote>
  <i>The basic function of government everywhere in all times, whatever title it adopts and whatever its origin and organisation may be, is always that of oppressing and exploiting the masses, of defending the oppressors and the exploiters: and its principal, characteristic and indispensable, instruments are the police agent and the tax-collector, the soldier and the gaoler — to whom must be invariably added the trader in lies, be he priest or schoolmaster, remunerated or protected by the government to enslave minds and make them docilely accept the yoke.</i>
</blockquote> If we accept the premise that the state holds a monopoly on violence be it physical or economic, then this framing of the state is quite useful to understand how it reinforces its power. In the case of physical violence, we see this in our modern police force and its priority of defending capital over human lives. As for economic violence, we see individuals trapped in an endless pursuit of basic needs like food, shelter, medical care, etc.. When these individuals are beaten down by a system stacked against them, we blame moral failings, yet in every financial crisis, we bail out capitalists despite their actual moral failings (greed, fraud, etc.). I found Malatesta's criticism of schooling to be equally intriguing. At the time this was written, our schooling system was very much meant to produce laborers as cogs in an industrialist machine. It's interesting to see that we're still having similar criticisms of our modern schooling like its failure to teach critical thinking or to prepare you for the "real world."<br /><br />Malatesta also points out how governments are good at expanding their reach into seemingly unrelated fields. Things that are important, but not necessarily the role of government. But once these become givens within our society, we come to view the state as untouchable because it would mean hurting such organs. For example, the state funds orphanages, runs the post office, or paves roads; all essential services, but not essential that they be provided by the state per se. Once again, I'm still working through my own thoughts regarding the role of the state. I'm not sure if I'm convinced that there are certain things that private individuals would handle better through free association than through pressure from the state. Universal healthcare comes to mind. How do you avoid free-riders and moral hazards without some governing body? <br /><br />I do however, agree with Malatesta's criticism of "mission creep" (in more modern parlance). <blockquote>
  <i>In the first place it is not true that once the social conditions are changed the nature and the role of government would change...Put an army in a country in which there are neither reasons for, nor fear of, war, civil or external, and it will provoke war or, if it does not succeed in its intentions, it will collapse. A police force where there are no crimes to solve or criminals to apprehend, will invent both, or cease to exist.</i>
</blockquote> I see this notion play out in the non-profit sector all the time. Basically, will an NGO ever work themselves out of a job? Not likely. Will a government ever fulfill its role if it means closing down a department? Probably not. The problem is the current organization of our society leaves people with very little choice. If my job is to eradicate homelessness in a city but in achieving my goal I would put myself and all of my fellow employees out of a job (losing income, health insurance, etc.) what incentive do I have to accomplish my job? Workers are incentivized to either expand their mission in ever-growing bloat or to drag out their work on an abysmally slow timeline so as to justify their continuation. Fully addressing this problem, however, would mean reimagining the provision of basic needs so that workers don't feel locked to a job.<br /><br />Another quote that I found interesting in framing the distinction between individuals and systems: <br /><blockquote>
  <i>The real being is man, the individual. Society or the collectivity — and the State or government which claims to represent it — if it is not a hollow abstraction, must be made up of individuals. And it is in the organism of every individual that all thoughts and human actions inevitably have their origin, and from being individual they become collective thoughts and acts when they are or become accepted by many individuals. Social action, therefore, is neither the negation nor the complement of individual initiative, but is the resultant of initiatives, thoughts and actions of all individuals who make up society; a resultant which, all other things being equal, is greater or smaller depending on whether individual forces are directed to a common objective or are divided or antagonistic.</i>
</blockquote><br /><br />Anyways, I'm still sorting through a lot of these ideas, but I think this was a great introduction to anarchism. I would definitely recommend this to anyone seeking to understand leftist political thought and its vision. <blockquote>
  <i>What is important is that a society should be brought into being in which the exploitation and domination of man by man is not possible; in which everybody has free access to the means of life, of development and of work, and that all can participate, as they wish and know how, in the organisation of social life.</i>
</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="2871634971645459870" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

