<div id="review_3332798556" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3332798556" />
    <a title="Marley" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2350757-marley"><img alt="Marley" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1246542865p2/2350757.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3332798556?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marley" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marley" href="/user/show/2350757-marley">Marley</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19418975-anarchy">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3332798556" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17224820819304618639">I first read Anarchy in the 1970s and it had a great influence on me. I still like it, but looking at at from today&apos;s Trump-ass perspetcive, Malatesta seems a bit naive and altruistic. People are shits and their main goal in life is to hold power over others. He forgot human nature.<br/><br/>Still, I think Malatesta lays anarchism , power theory and structure and class struggle out very well.<br/> <br/>In the 19th century anarchism, socialism, and communism were often interchangeable in a general sense--especially </span>
  <span id="freeText17224820819304618639" style="display:none">I first read Anarchy in the 1970s and it had a great influence on me. I still like it, but looking at at from today's Trump-ass perspetcive, Malatesta seems a bit naive and altruistic. People are shits and their main goal in life is to hold power over others. He forgot human nature.<br /><br />Still, I think Malatesta lays anarchism , power theory and structure and class struggle out very well.<br /> <br />In the 19th century anarchism, socialism, and communism were often interchangeable in a general sense--especially as defined by the capitalist and liberal classes--but there are many differences. So, too, there was much hostility among socialists, communists, and anarchists, and that has certainly grown in the 20th and 21st centuries. I remember sitting around Oberlin back in 1972 ridiculing commies, socialists, and their SDS hangers on. Simply put, they were statists, and anarchists were and are not. Socialism/Communism is just trading one one evil for another. Plenty of people learned that the hard way after World War 1.<br /><br />Anarchy is really a primer. You have to read Malatesta collections to get the real picture of Malatesta and his ideas. He's one of the greats.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17224820819304618639" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


