<div id="review_2756121826" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2756121826" />
    <a title="Clare" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10616643-clare"><img alt="Clare" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1341170929p2/10616643.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2756121826?book_show_action=true">Mar 19, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clare" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clare" href="/user/show/10616643-clare">Clare</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2756121826" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2339269891602918088">Doing some Anarchism 101 reading for DSA reasons. One thing I like about anarchist lit thus far is that they publish a lot of short, accessible things -- pamphlets and zines and the like. The other best bit is that much of it is available for free, either because it is very old or because anarchists DGAF about their copyrights.<br/><br/>One of the famous ones of these is <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/search/search?q=%20Errico%20Maltesta' title=' Errico Maltesta' rel='nofollow noopener'> Errico Maltesta</a>&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/450297.Anarchy' title='Anarchy by Errico Malatesta' rel='nofollow noopener'> Anarchy</a>, a pamphlet or essay laying out the very basics of what &quot;anarchism&quot; means and what anarchists believe. It is</span>
  <span id="freeText2339269891602918088" style="display:none">Doing some Anarchism 101 reading for DSA reasons. One thing I like about anarchist lit thus far is that they publish a lot of short, accessible things -- pamphlets and zines and the like. The other best bit is that much of it is available for free, either because it is very old or because anarchists DGAF about their copyrights.<br /><br />One of the famous ones of these is <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/search/search?q=%20Errico%20Maltesta" title=" Errico Maltesta" rel="nofollow noopener"> Errico Maltesta</a>'s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/450297.Anarchy" title="Anarchy by Errico Malatesta" rel="nofollow noopener"> Anarchy</a>, a pamphlet or essay laying out the very basics of what "anarchism" means and what anarchists believe. It is obviously not very theoretically dense and does not rebut every anticipatable argument, because if it did, it would be a lot longer. But it does give you a decent taste of how anarchists define concepts like "government" and "the state" and quite what they think about them (spoilers: they're against 'em).<br /><br />Originally posted at <a href="https://bloodygranuaile.dreamwidth.org/425142.html" rel="nofollow noopener">The state of a people without any constituted authority</a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2339269891602918088" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


